        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To map the core population of SDC335, we propose to perform a 92 pointing mosaic (half-beam spaced - covering a rectangular region of 160"*90") of the 1.4mm dust continuum emission (220 GHz - band 6) using the C34-3 configuration. This will provide us an angular resolution of $\sim 0.6\arcsec$. This set-up  is optimal since it allows us to reach our resolution requirement (2000 AU at 3.25kpc, cf proposal).Based on our simulations, a 1Msun core at 10K, with an intrinsic size of 2000~AU, has a peak density flux around 0.15 mJy/0.6"-beam. Therefore to get a 3sigma detection on such source, we require a rms  sigma=0.05 mJy/0.6"-beam. The bandwidth we are using for this noise calculation is the one resulting from the aggregation of the 4 spectral windows of 1.875GHz bandwidth each, for a total of 7.5GHz bandwidth. The PWV assumed is 1.26mm (4th octile).With these parameters, we require a total on-source time of 3.49h, for a total telescope time of 6.96h.

Simultaneously, we will observe CH3CN(12-11) and the H2CO(3-2) (in two different spectral windows),necessary to get an estimate of the kinetic temperature toward the cores. The shortest separation between 2 consecutive K components of CH3CN (K=0 to K=1) is 4.3MHz (6km/s at 220GHz). High spectral resolution is not critical for the temperature estimate, and therefore a velocity resolution of 2 km/s is enough to fit the K-ladder of both lines. According to previous observations of H2CO(3-2) toward dense cores (e.g. Rodon et al. 2012), 1Msun cores have brightness temperatures around 1K (on similar spatial scales as the observations proposed here). According to the time estimator, during the time required for continuum observations, we will be able to  get a 4 to 5sigma detection on these 1K lines, in a 2~km/s channel.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
