    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The observed universality of the IMF bears strong consequences on the star formation process. In particular, it implies that in star-forming clouds, at any time of their evolution, the mass distribution of high-density, small-scale cores (for which the SFE is near 100%) must have a simlar shape to the IMF. This seems to have been broadly observed in low-mass star-forming regions, but has never really ben observed in massive star-forming regions, mostly because of the difficulty of such observations. Here, we propose to map the core mass distribution of the SDC335 OB cluster progenitor. This IRDC has a central massive protostellar source (500Msun gas in 0.05pc diameter) implying that a wealth of lower mass cores should be present, but so far remain undetected. By mapping the mass distributinon of this core we would be able if it is consistent with the universality of the IMF, but also, by investigating core mass segregation, test the already proposed scenario of cloud global collapse for the formation of the most massive stars. </prp:abstract>
